Klemens von Metternich, "the last great European" per Evola.

Franz Matzke is a 30s German "Neue Sachlichkeit" writer whom J. Evola briefly mentions, who today seems an absolutely obscure figure, without even a Wikipedia page. But the esthetic sensibilities he describes strikingly reflect those of young people today: anti-romantic, inhuman.

"Beauty for Matzke is a name that applies to human endeavours, not nature: in his view, there are no landscapes ‘more beautiful’ than others, but only those which are more distant, more boundless, more serene, harsher, or colder than others." Glaciers, fjords, tropical suns, etc.
It's from "Neue Sachlichkeit’: The Credo of the New German Generations" but one wonders if this was causal or prophetic

Matzke defines the traits of the "new Nordic generation" as: avoiding emotional outbursts, calmness of being, "love of distance", being reserved in the midst of crowds, impersonality and a "vanishing of man", a "medieval anonymity", keeping tragedies private, lack of vain "self".

There is revulsion to collective bonding, masses, but "individualism" as a concept is also forgotten. Both morbid erotic obsessions and a "drama" of unrequited fatal passionate love feel foreign. Everything becomes clearer, colder, acquires an icy metallic taste. Hearts are cold.
Evola quoting Matzke; might as well have been written today instead of 90 years ago.

Arthur Jones writes his father was a medical doctor and when he was a kid, he worked office hours from 8 in the morning to midnight; 16 hours; THEN performed elective surgeries in the small hours of the night. 7 days a week. Basically no deep sleep ever. $150.00 per month salary.

His mother was also trying to get into medical school at the time, after finishing college, but didn't have enough credits or whatever so she had to go back for two more college years. The sheer tolerance for monstrous levels of stress people had at that time is incomprehensible.
